@node Overview
@chapter Overview

@samp{kmacro-extras.el} extends Emacs' built-in keyboard macro system
(@samp{kmacro.el}).  The stock macro counter can insert sequential numbers
(1, 2, 3, @dots{}) during macro execution, but switching to alphabetical
sequences (a, b, c, @dots{}) requires manually changing the counter format
and resetting the counter value---two separate operations that are easy
to forget.  This package wraps both steps into a single toggle command.

@node Commands
@chapter Commands

@menu
* Toggling the counter format::
@end menu

@node Toggling the counter format
@section Toggling the counter format

@findex kmacro-extras-counter-toggle-alpha-number
The command @code{kmacro-extras-counter-toggle-alpha-number} switches the
keyboard macro counter between numeric and alphabetical mode:

@itemize
@item
When the current format is numeric (@samp{%d}), the command sets the
format to @samp{%c} (character) and resets the counter to 97, the ASCII
code for @samp{a}.  Subsequent insertions via @code{kmacro-insert-counter}
will produce @samp{a}, @samp{b}, @samp{c}, and so on.
@item
When the current format is alphabetical (@samp{%c}), the command sets it
back to @samp{%d} and resets the counter to 1.
@end itemize

This is especially handy when you need to label items with letters in
one macro and switch back to numbers for the next, without
interrupting your editing flow.  A confirmation message (@samp{"Set to
alphabetical"} or @samp{"Set to numeric"}) is displayed in the echo area
after each toggle.

